replies.bodyText:
My thinking on this:

The number of use cases for n-streams will be decreasing as n is increasing. Therefore when (if) we do penta, hexa will bring even more diminishing results.
This could all be solved with dynamic cardinality streams, that can handle any number of parameters. (Essentially varargs.)
However, that would not be done with Java generics. In this kind of work, generics is the one thing that keeps me sane. If all I had throughout constraint streams were Objects, I would have gone mad.

All in all, if we have to add more streams, I'd much rather go for Penta than for Dynamic.
replies.author: triceo

replies.bodyText: One more thing to note - with dynamic cardinality streams not only would Lukas lose the type safety, but users as well.
replies.author: rsynek

replies.bodyText:
At some point, we will need to support dynamic cardinality streams. We can argue whether that's at Penta, Hexa, septi, octo, novem, ..., novemnonagint, centi or higher ;) As indeed users lose type safetly.
As for the design, I was thinking of PolyConstraintStream extends AbstractConstraintStream<Object[]>. Either way: out of scope for now (poly and penta).

I noticed there is a potential for some other combinations, e.g.:

3 grouping functions, no collector => TriStream
3 grouping functions, 1 collector => QuadStream

But as discussed, these might be added later.
